1	\chapter{The Abel--Jacobi map}
2	\label{chap:AbelJacobi}
3	
4	Let $C$ be a smooth proper curve over $k$ as in Chapter~\ref{chap:Genus}, and let $\Jac(C)$ be its Jacobian (Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian}).
5	
6	\section{Definition}
7	
8	\begin{definition}[Abel--Jacobi map]
9	  \label{def:ofCurve}
10	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.ofCurve}
11	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
12	  Given a $k$-rational point $P \colon \Spec k \to C$ --- equivalently, a morphism $P \colon \mathbf 1 \to C$ in the category of $k$-schemes --- the \emph{Abel--Jacobi map} is the $k$-morphism
13	  \[
14	    \alpha_P \colon C \;\longrightarrow\; \Jac(C),\qquad Q \;\longmapsto\; [\mathcal O_C(Q - P)].
15	  \]
16	  Functorially, it is the morphism in the category of $k$-schemes induced by the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$ on $C \times C$ via the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$.
17	\end{definition}
18	
19	\section{Pointed property}
20	
21	\begin{lemma}[$\alpha_P$ sends $P$ to $0$]
22	  \label{lem:comp_ofCurve}
23	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.comp_ofCurve}
24	  \uses{def:ofCurve}
25	  $P \;\circ\; \alpha_P \;=\; \eta[\Jac(C)]$, where $\eta[\Jac(C)]$ is the identity element of the group scheme $\Jac(C)$.
26	\end{lemma}
27	
28	\begin{proof}
29	  \uses{def:ofCurve}
30	  At the level of $k$-points: $\alpha_P(P) = [\mathcal O_C(P - P)] = [\mathcal O_C] = 0$. Globally: by construction, $\alpha_P$ is the morphism classifying the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$; restricting to the section $(P, \mathrm{id})$ gives the trivial line bundle, hence the zero point of $\Pic^0$.
31	\end{proof}
32	
33	\section{Universal (Albanese) property}
34	
35	\begin{theorem}[Albanese property of the Jacobian]
36	  \label{thm:exists_unique_ofCurve_comp}
37	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.exists_unique_ofCurve_comp}
38	  \uses{def:ofCurve, lem:comp_ofCurve}
39	  Let $A$ be an abelian variety over $k$ --- i.e.\ a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $k$. For every pointed morphism $f \colon C \to A$ with $f \circ P = \eta[A]$, there exists a unique group-scheme morphism $g \colon \Jac(C) \to A$ such that $f = g \circ \alpha_P$.
40	  \[
41	  \begin{array}{ccc}
42	    C & \stackrel{f}{\longrightarrow} & A \\
43	    {\scriptstyle\alpha_P} \downarrow & \nearrow {\scriptstyle\exists ! g} & \\
44	    \Jac(C) & &
45	  \end{array}
46	  \]
47	\end{theorem}
48	
49	\begin{proof}
50	  \uses{def:IsAlbanese, thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness, thm:IsAlbanese_unique}
51	  By Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, there exists a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $J$ over $k$ of dimension $g(C)$ such that, for every marked point $P \in C(k)$, the scheme $J$ together with a morphism $\iota_P \colon C \to J$ with $\iota_P \circ P = \eta_J$ satisfies the Albanese universal property of Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}. The Jacobian $\Jac(C)$ is defined as this scheme $J$, and the Abel--Jacobi map $\alpha_P$ of Definition~\ref{def:ofCurve} is the universal morphism $\iota_P$ associated with the chosen marked point $P$.
52	
53	  Existence and uniqueness of the factorisation $g$ are then exactly the universal-property data carried by $\iota_P$ in Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}: for every pointed $f \colon C \to A$ with $f \circ P = \eta_A$, there exists a unique $g \colon J \to A$ with $f = \iota_P \circ g$. Both the higher-genus content and the genus-$0$ rigidity (i.e.\ that every morphism from a genus-$0$ pointed curve to an abelian variety is constant) are absorbed into Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}.
54	\end{proof}
55	
56	\section{Implementation route via the Albanese framework}
57	
58	The three results above are formalised through the Albanese framework of Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}. In the absence of Mathlib's Pic-scheme machinery, the Jacobian is defined as an Albanese object for every marked point (Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}); the universal-property data $(\iota_P, \text{factorisation})$ is then carried by the Albanese predicate (Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}) and projects directly into the three results of this chapter. Existence of a uniform-over-$P$ Albanese object is the single remaining mathematical hypothesis pending the formalisation of either Pic-scheme representability, symmetric-power quotients, or the rigidity theorem $\Hom(\mathbb P^1_k, A) = A(k)$ in Mathlib.
59	
60	The classical proof via line bundles --- using the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$, dual abelian varieties, and the rigidity theorem of Mumford \S4 --- gives the same conclusion but requires more Mathlib infrastructure. The Albanese-framework route used here is mathematically equivalent and bundles all of the missing infrastructure into the single hypothesis of Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}.
61

1	\chapter{The sheaf of relative differentials}
2	\label{chap:differentials}
3	
4	This chapter develops the sheaf of relative K\"ahler differentials $\Omega_{X/S}$ of a morphism of schemes $X \to S$, starting from the ring-theoretic K\"ahler differential module $\Omega_{B/A}$ already available in Mathlib. The output is a quasi-coherent sheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules characterised by its restriction to affine opens: for any affine open $V = \Spec B \subseteq X$ lying over an affine open $U = \Spec A \subseteq S$, the sections satisfy
5	\[
6	  \Omega_{X/S}(V) \;=\; \Omega_{B/A}.
7	\]
8	
9	The downstream role of this chapter is twofold. First, the smoothness hypothesis on the curve $C \to \Spec k$ that appears in the Jacobian definition and the Abel--Jacobi map amounts to the condition that $\Omega_{C/k}$ is locally free of rank one; this characterisation is what unlocks the dimension computation $g(C) = \dim_k H^0(C, \Omega_{C/k}) = \dim_k H^1(C, \struct{C})$. Second, the cotangent space at the identity section of $\Jac(C)$ is $\Omega_{\Jac(C)/k}$ pulled back along the unit $e \colon \Spec k \to \Jac(C)$; the relative dimension of $\Jac(C)$ that appears in the smoothness statement is read off from this tangent space.
10	
11	\section{The relative cotangent sheaf}
12	
13	\begin{definition}[Relative cotangent presheaf of a morphism]
14	  \label{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}
15	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.relativeDifferentialsPresheaf}
16	  Let $f \colon X \to S$ be a morphism of schemes. For each pair of affine opens $U \subseteq S$, $V \subseteq X$ with $f(V) \subseteq U$, write $A = \struct{S}(U)$ and $B = \struct{X}(V)$, and use the $f$-induced ring map $A \to B$. The K\"ahler differential module $\Omega_{B/A}$ is then a $B$-module, hence a section over $V$ of a presheaf on $X$. The collection of these modules, together with the natural restriction maps along inclusions of affine opens, defines a presheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules on $X$.
17	\end{definition}
18	
19	\begin{theorem}[Sheaf condition for $\Omega_{X/S}$]
20	  \label{thm:relative_kaehler_isSheaf}
21	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.relativeDifferentialsPresheaf_isSheaf}
22	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf}
23	  The relative cotangent presheaf is a sheaf in the Zariski topology on $X$. The proof reduces to the sheaf condition on the basis of affine basic opens, where it is the localisation compatibility $\Omega_{B[1/f]/A} \cong \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f]$ of the K\"ahler differential module; descent from a basis to all opens is standard.
24	\end{theorem}
25	
26	\begin{definition}[Relative cotangent sheaf $\Omega_{X/S}$]
27	  \label{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
28	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.relativeDifferentials}
29	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_presheaf, thm:relative_kaehler_isSheaf}
30	  The sheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules associated with the relative cotangent presheaf is the \emph{sheaf of relative differentials} $\Omega_{X/S}$. It is quasi-coherent.
31	\end{definition}
32	
33	\begin{remark}[Comparison with Mathlib's ring-level $\Omega_{B/A}$]
34	  \label{rem:kahler_compatibility}
35	  Mathlib provides the ring-theoretic K\"ahler differential module $\Omega_{B/A}$ together with the universal derivation $\mathrm{d} \colon B \to \Omega_{B/A}$. The construction of $\Omega_{X/S}$ on affine opens is, by definition, this Mathlib module. The derivative-of-localisation isomorphism $\Omega_{B[1/f]/A} \cong \Omega_{B/A} \otimes_B B[1/f]$ is precisely what makes the affine-restriction presheaf into a sheaf.
36	\end{remark}
37	
38	\section{Universal property and the cotangent exact sequence}
39	
40	\begin{definition}[Universal derivation]
41	  \label{def:universal_derivation}
42	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.universalDerivation}
43	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
44	  The morphism of sheaves of abelian groups $\mathrm{d} \colon \struct{X} \to \Omega_{X/S}$, defined on each affine open $V = \Spec B$ over $\Spec A$ by the Mathlib universal derivation $\mathrm{d}_{B/A} \colon B \to \Omega_{B/A}$, is the \emph{universal derivation}. It is an $A$-linear sheaf map satisfying the Leibniz rule $\mathrm{d}(ab) = a \mathrm{d}(b) + b \mathrm{d}(a)$.
45	\end{definition}
46	
47	The cotangent exact sequence is decomposed into three named ingredients before being assembled into a single theorem.
48	
49	\begin{definition}[Base-change cotangent map $\alpha$]
50	  \label{def:cotangent_alpha}
51	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangentExactSeqAlpha}
52	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
53	  For schemes $X \xrightarrow{f} Y \xrightarrow{g} S$ the \emph{base-change cotangent map} is the natural morphism of quasi-coherent $\struct{X}$-modules
54	  \[
55	    \alpha \colon f^*\Omega_{Y/S} \;\longrightarrow\; \Omega_{X/S}
56	  \]
57	  whose local description on an affine chart with rings $A = \struct{S}(W)$, $A' = \struct{Y}(f(V))$, $B = \struct{X}(V)$ is the standard map $\Omega_{A'/A} \otimes_{A'} B \to \Omega_{B/A}$ of K\"ahler differentials, $da \otimes b \mapsto b \cdot da$.
58	\end{definition}
59	
60	\begin{definition}[Relative-quotient cotangent map $\beta$]
61	  \label{def:cotangent_beta}
62	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangentExactSeqBeta}
63	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
64	  For schemes $X \xrightarrow{f} Y \xrightarrow{g} S$ the \emph{relative-quotient cotangent map} is the natural surjection of quasi-coherent $\struct{X}$-modules
65	  \[
66	    \beta \colon \Omega_{X/S} \;\longrightarrow\; \Omega_{X/Y}
67	  \]
68	  whose local description on an affine chart $A \to A' \to B$ is the surjection $\Omega_{B/A} \to \Omega_{B/A'}$ that kills the $A$-linear derivations factoring through $A'$.
69	\end{definition}
70	
71	\begin{lemma}[Exactness of the cotangent short complex]
72	  \label{lem:cotangent_exact_structure}
73	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangentExactSeq_structure}
74	  \uses{def:cotangent_alpha, def:cotangent_beta}
75	  The composition $\beta \circ \alpha$ vanishes, the resulting short complex is exact at the middle term, and $\beta$ is an epimorphism. The three ingredients are local statements whose ring-level inputs are the exactness of the Mathlib cotangent sequence $\Omega_{A'/A} \otimes_{A'} B \to \Omega_{B/A} \to \Omega_{B/A'} \to 0$, together with the surjectivity of the right-hand map.
76	\end{lemma}
77	
78	\begin{theorem}[Cotangent exact sequence for a composition]
79	  \label{thm:cotangent_exact_sequence}
80	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangent_exact_sequence}
81	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf, def:universal_derivation, def:cotangent_alpha, def:cotangent_beta, lem:cotangent_exact_structure}
82	  For schemes $X \xrightarrow{f} Y \xrightarrow{g} S$, there is an exact sequence of quasi-coherent $\struct{X}$-modules
83	  \[
84	    f^*\Omega_{Y/S} \;\xrightarrow{\;\alpha\;}\; \Omega_{X/S} \;\xrightarrow{\;\beta\;}\;
85	      \Omega_{X/Y} \;\longrightarrow\; 0,
86	  \]
87	  with $\alpha$ and $\beta$ as above. It follows by bundling the three claims of Lemma~\ref{lem:cotangent_exact_structure}.
88	\end{theorem}
89	
90	\section{Smoothness and local freeness of $\Omega$}
91	
92	\begin{theorem}[Smoothness in terms of $\Omega$]
93	  \label{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
94	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
95	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
96	  Let $f \colon X \to S$ be a finite-presentation morphism of schemes. Then $f$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$ if and only if $\Omega_{X/S}$ is locally free of rank $n$ as a sheaf of $\struct{X}$-modules. The forward direction is the Jacobian criterion; the converse follows from the cotangent exact sequence and Nakayama's lemma applied at each point.
97	\end{theorem}
98	
99	\begin{corollary}[Cotangent space at a section]
100	  \label{cor:cotangent_at_section}
101	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cotangent_at_section}
102	  \uses{thm:smooth_iff_locally_free_omega}
103	  If $f \colon X \to S$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$ and $s \colon S \to X$ is a section of $f$, then the cotangent space $s^*\Omega_{X/S}$ is a locally free $\struct{S}$-module of rank $n$. In particular, if $S = \Spec k$ is a field point and $X$ is smooth of relative dimension $n$, the cotangent space at the corresponding $k$-point is an $n$-dimensional $k$-vector space.
104	\end{corollary}
105	
106	\section{Curves and the canonical sheaf}
107	
108	The case of a smooth proper curve $C \to \Spec k$ is the special case $n = 1$: the relative cotangent sheaf $\Omega_{C/k}$ is a line bundle on $C$, classically denoted $\omega_C$ and called the \emph{canonical sheaf}.
109	
110	\begin{theorem}[Serre-duality genus equality]
111	  \label{thm:serre_duality_genus}
112	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.serre_duality_genus}
113	  \uses{def:relative_kaehler_sheaf}
114	  Let $C$ be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve over a field $k$. Then
115	  \[
116	    \dim_k H^0(C, \Omega_{C/k}) \;=\; \dim_k H^1(C, \struct{C}).
117	  \]
118	  Both sides equal the genus $g(C)$. The equality is the dimension one case of Serre duality applied to the canonical sheaf; combined with the definition $g(C) = \dim_k H^1(C, \struct{C})$, this provides the alternative differential-theoretic characterisation used when computing the relative dimension of $\Jac(C)$ at the identity.
119	\end{theorem}
120

1	\chapter{The Jacobian as an abelian variety}
2	\label{chap:Jacobian}
3	
4	Let $C$ be a smooth proper curve over $k$ in the sense of Chapter~\ref{chap:Genus}, with genus $g = g(C)$.
5	
6	Because the Picard-scheme machinery (Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}) is blocked at the level of monoidal-category infrastructure for $\mathcal O_X$-modules and the full FGA representability theorem, this chapter builds the Jacobian by an alternative ad-hoc route: the Albanese functor on smooth proper curves.
7	
8	\section{The Albanese construction}
9	
10	For a smooth proper curve $C$ over $k$, the Albanese variety is the universal abelian variety receiving a morphism from $C$. Over an algebraically closed field this is classically identified with the connected component of the identity of the Picard scheme, but we construct it directly from symmetric powers.
11	
12	\subsection{Symmetric powers and the Abel--Jacobi map}
13	
14	Let $C^{(g)} = \Sym^g(C)$ be the $g$\textsuperscript{th} symmetric power of $C$ (the quotient of $C^g$ by the action of the symmetric group $S_g$). It is a smooth proper scheme over $k$ of dimension $g$. Fix a $k$-rational point $P_0 \in C(k)$. The map
15	\[
16	  \sigma \colon C^{(g)} \longrightarrow \Pic^g_{C/k}, \qquad
17	  \sum_{i=1}^g [P_i] \longmapsto \mathcal O_C\bigl(\textstyle\sum_{i=1}^g P_i - g P_0\bigr)
18	\]
19	is surjective and birational onto its image; its fibres are projective spaces (Brill--Noether--Riemann--Roch). Choosing $P_0$ gives a translation isomorphism $\Pic^g_{C/k} \xrightarrow{\;\sim\;} \Pic^0_{C/k}$, and the Stein factorisation of $\sigma$ yields the Jacobian as the connected component of the identity.
20	
21	In the Lean formalisation we do not have general symmetric powers of schemes (or quotients by finite group actions) in Mathlib. We therefore take a more direct approach: we define the Jacobian as the Albanese object of $C$ inside the category of smooth proper group schemes over $k$, using the universal property and the known dimension formula.
22	
23	\subsection{The Albanese universal property}
24	
25	\begin{definition}[Albanese universal property of a pointed curve]
26	  \label{def:IsAlbanese}
27	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.IsAlbanese}
28	  Let $(C, P)$ be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve over $k$ with a marked $k$-rational point $P \in C(k)$. A smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $J$ over $k$ is an \emph{Albanese object} for $(C, P)$ if there exists a morphism $\iota \colon C \to J$ sending $P$ to the identity element $\eta \in J$, and such that every morphism $f \colon C \to A$ from $C$ to a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $A$ with $f(P) = \eta_A$ factors uniquely as $f = \iota \circ g$ for some morphism of group schemes $g \colon J \to A$.
29	\end{definition}
30	
31	\begin{theorem}[Uniqueness of the Albanese object]
32	  \label{thm:IsAlbanese_unique}
33	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.IsAlbanese.unique}
34	  \uses{def:IsAlbanese}
35	  Any two Albanese objects for the same pointed curve $(C, P)$ are uniquely isomorphic by an isomorphism compatible with their universal morphisms. The proof is the standard universal-property argument: each of the two universal morphisms factors through the other, the two composites equal the unique self-factorisation $\mathrm{id}$, hence each factorisation is an isomorphism.
36	\end{theorem}
37	
38	\subsection{The Jacobian definition}
39	
40	\begin{definition}[Jacobian]
41	  \label{def:Jacobian}
42	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian}
43	  \uses{def:genus, def:IsAlbanese, thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}
44	  The \emph{Jacobian} of $C$ is the abelian variety $\Jac(C)$ over $k$ obtained as the Albanese object of $C$: a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $k$ of dimension $g(C)$ equipped with a universal morphism $C \to \Jac(C)$ (for each choice of marked point). It is viewed as an object of the category of $k$-schemes over $\Spec k$. Formally, $\Jac(C)$ is defined as the underlying scheme of a (uniform-over-$P$) Albanese witness for $C$ provided by Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}.
45	
46	  When $g(C) = 0$ the Jacobian collapses to $\Spec k$ itself, which is the terminal object in the category of $k$-schemes. When $g(C) > 0$ the underlying scheme is the abelian variety produced by Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}; the genus-one case recovers $C$ itself (after choosing a $k$-rational point), and the higher genus case yields the non-trivial $g$-dimensional abelian variety. Both cases are handled uniformly: $\Jac(C)$ is the underlying scheme of the Albanese witness, with no special-case branching at the level of the definition. The genus-$0$ specialisation is implicit in the fact that any group scheme over $k$ of relative dimension $0$ is isomorphic to $\Spec k$.
47	\end{definition}
48	
49	\section{Group scheme structure and abelian-variety properties}
50	
51	\begin{theorem}[Group object structure]
52	  \label{thm:Jacobian_grpObj}
53	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.instGrpObj}
54	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
55	  $\Jac(C)$ carries a canonical group-object structure in the category of $k$-schemes over $\Spec k$, induced by the Albanese universal property and the cogroup structure of $C$ in the category of pointed curves.
56	\end{theorem}
57	
58	\begin{theorem}[Smoothness and dimension]
59	  \label{thm:Jacobian_smooth_genus}
60	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.smoothOfRelativeDimension_genus}
61	  \uses{def:Jacobian, def:genus}
62	  $\Jac(C) \to \Spec k$ is smooth of relative dimension $g(C)$.
63	\end{theorem}
64	
65	\begin{theorem}[Properness]
66	  \label{thm:Jacobian_proper}
67	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.instIsProper}
68	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
69	  $\Jac(C) \to \Spec k$ is proper.
70	\end{theorem}
71	
72	\begin{theorem}[Geometric irreducibility]
73	  \label{thm:Jacobian_geomIrred}
74	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.instGeometricallyIrreducible}
75	  \uses{def:Jacobian}
76	  $\Jac(C) \to \Spec k$ is geometrically irreducible.
77	\end{theorem}
78	
79	All four properties are part of the Albanese construction. Smoothness and dimension follow from the deformation-theoretic identification of the tangent space at the identity with $H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$ (Phase~A, Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_StructureSheafAb}). Properness and geometric irreducibility descend from the corresponding properties of $C$ because the Albanese map is surjective with connected fibres.
80	
81	\subsection{Sanity check in low genus}
82	
83	\begin{itemize}
84	  \item $g = 0$: Then $\Jac(C) = \Spec k$, the trivial group scheme; $\Jac(\mathbb P^1_k) = \Spec k$ is smooth of relative dimension $0 = g$.
85	  \item $g = 1$: Then $\Jac(C) \cong C$ once a $k$-rational point on $C$ is fixed; $C$ is itself an elliptic curve (abelian variety of dimension $1$).
86	  \item $g \ge 2$: $\Jac(C)$ is a non-trivial $g$-dimensional abelian variety, never isomorphic to $C$ as a scheme.
87	\end{itemize}
88	
89	\section{Existence of an Albanese variety}
90	
91	The classical construction of the Jacobian goes through the Picard scheme machinery: $\Jac(C)$ is the connected component of the identity of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$. An equivalent route, available whenever a $k$-rational point $P \in C(k)$ has been fixed, is to take the Stein factorisation of the Abel--Jacobi morphism $\Sym^g(C) \to \Pic^g_{C/k}$ and translate by $-gP$.
92	
93	\begin{theorem}[Existence of an Albanese variety uniformly over the marked point]
94	  \label{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}
95	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.nonempty_jacobianWitness}
96	  \uses{def:IsAlbanese, def:Jacobian, def:genus}
97	  Let $C$ be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve over a field $k$. There exists a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $J$ over $k$ of relative dimension $g(C)$ such that, for every $k$-rational point $P \in C(k)$, the scheme $J$ is an Albanese object for the pointed curve $(C, P)$ in the sense of Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}.
98	\end{theorem}
99	
100	\begin{proof}
101	  \uses{def:IsAlbanese}
102	  The underlying scheme $J$ depends only on $C$, not on the choice of marked point; only the universal morphism $\iota_P \colon C \to J$ varies with $P$. Two classical constructions provide $J$:
103	  \begin{itemize}
104	    \item $g(C) \ge 1$: (i) take $J = \Pic^0_{C/k}$, the connected component of the identity of the Picard scheme; for every $P \in C(k)$, the Abel--Jacobi map $\iota_P \colon C \to \Pic^0_{C/k}$, $Q \mapsto [\mathcal O_C(Q - P)]$, sends $P$ to the identity and satisfies the universal property by the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$. Equivalently, (ii) form the Stein factorisation of $\Sym^g(C) \to \Pic^g_{C/k}$ translated by $-gP$. Both routes yield a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme of dimension $g(C)$.
105	    \item $g(C) = 0$: take $J = \Spec k$, the trivial $k$-group scheme of dimension $0$. The Albanese universal property in this case reduces to the rigidity assertion that every morphism $f \colon C \to A$ from a smooth proper geometrically irreducible genus-$0$ curve $C$ to a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $A$ with $f(P) = \eta_A$ is the constant morphism at $\eta_A$. Classically, this follows from $\Hom(\mathbb P^1_k, A) = A(k)$ together with the fact that a genus-$0$ curve with a $k$-rational point is isomorphic to $\mathbb P^1_k$ (Brauer--Severi). The unique morphism $\Spec k \to A$ then provides the required factorisation.
106	  \end{itemize}
107	  Mathlib currently contains neither Pic-scheme representability, nor symmetric powers / quotients of schemes by finite group actions, nor the rigidity theorem $\Hom(\mathbb P^1_k, A) = A(k)$ for morphisms to abelian varieties. The existence statement is therefore recorded here as a single working hypothesis backing all downstream consequences (the four protected instances on $\Jac(C)$, the Abel--Jacobi map and its universal property of Chapter~\ref{chap:AbelJacobi}). Both the higher-genus existence and the genus-$0$ rigidity content are encapsulated in this single hypothesis.
108	\end{proof}
109	
110	\section{Implementation route via the Albanese functor}
111	
112	Because the full Picard-scheme representability theorem is not available in current Mathlib, the formal construction proceeds in two layers:
113	
114	\begin{enumerate}
115	  \item \textbf{Layer I --- direct definition.} The Jacobian of $C$ is defined uniformly as the underlying scheme of the Albanese witness provided by Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, carrying the four properties of Theorems~\ref{thm:Jacobian_grpObj}--\ref{thm:Jacobian_geomIrred} (each obtained by projection from the witness). The genus-$0$ case is included: the witness's universal property in that case implicitly carries the rigidity content $\Hom(\mathbb P^1_k, A) = A(k)$.
116	
